From: nvukobratTT <nvukobrat@tenstorrent.com>
Subject: [PATCH v2] TTNNCheckDRAMBudget: replace sum estimator with first-fit freelist simulation

TASK-021 introduced a simple running-sum estimator for peak DRAM usage.
That gives a lower bound only — it cannot detect fragmentation-induced
OOMs where total free DRAM is sufficient but no single contiguous block
large enough for the requested tensor exists.

The specific motivating case: Mochi 10B at seq_len=2080 on 4-chip SPMD TP
OOMs at runtime despite an estimated ~12–14 GiB peak vs a 34 GiB budget,
because the first-fit allocator inside tt-metal cannot pack non-contiguous
free regions for a single large contiguous allocation.

This patch replaces the inner simulation loop with a minimal first-fit
FreeListAllocator.  For each Value produced by an op the allocator does a
first-fit search over the current free ranges (sorted by base address).  On
DeallocateOp the range is returned and adjacent ranges are merged.  If at
any point the allocator cannot satisfy an allocation but total free bytes
would have been sufficient, the pass emits a distinct
"fragmentation-induced DRAM OOM" error that names the exact contiguous
block requested, the largest currently-available block, and the total free
bytes.  If the total budget is simply exceeded the existing error path is
preserved unchanged.

DRAM allocations in tt-metal are aligned to 32 bytes (L1_ALIGNMENT); the
allocator rounds all requests up accordingly.

For symmetric SPMD TP models the IR already reflects per-chip tensor sizes
after the SPMD sharding pass, so a single per-function freelist with the
per-chip budget is sufficient.

Fixes: https://github.com/nvukobratTT/tt-xla/issues/11 (Solution 3 v2)
